Juchari Ziranhua / Nuestros Raices / Our Roots
Along the way: Snapping!, Crackling!, and Popping!
Swarm
fields.description: A colorful mural of bees, honeycombs and wildflowers spans the entire brick wall on the side of the Burt’s Bees building. “Swarm” is part of the Good of the Hive Initiative which is painting 50,000 honey bees across America to raise awareness of the decline of bees and their importance in our world.

fields.title: Pauli Murray from the Face Up
Liberty Warehouse Mural
fields.description: Tucked in an open courtyard of the Liberty Warehouse Apartments, this 45 foot-long mural represents a history of the original Liberty Warehouse that once occupied this site and the legacy of tobacco that was a central industry in Durham. Elements of the mural include Major the Bull, the Lucky Strike water tower, Liberty Cafe and other buildings, and men inspecting tobacco leaves prior to auction.

fields.title: Two Way Bridges
fields.description: A handshake represents trust and agreement between two people. This mural of clasping hands beneath the gaze of two eyes is called “Two Way Bridges” or “Puentes de Doble Via.” It is part of a broader Two Way Bridges project that connects and deepens exchanges between Duke University and the local Latino community (source: muraldurham.com).

A Legacy of Community and Institutional Connections
Tobacco and E.J. Parish
fields.description: Tobacco and E.J. Parrish is the first in a series of six monuments along Parrish Street celebrating the history of “Black Wall Street” in Durham. Featuring five large tobacco leaves above a plaque, the sculpture honors early tobacco entrepreneur E.J. Parrish who operated a tobacco warehouse on Parrish Street in the late 19th century (source: https://docsouth.unc.edu/commland/monument/194/).

fields.title: The Art of the Warli in Durham
fields.description: This sprawling, lace-like mural of intricate white images on a brick background was created in the style of Warli - an indigenous art style from Western India that uses minimalistic forms and vibrant patterns to reflect everyday lives and events. Members of the Durham community worked with the artists in a series of live-streamed lessons to learn Warli painting techniques and contribute sketches about Durham to be included in the mural’s design. The mural was created as part of Season 3 of Downtown Durham Inc’s Public Space Project (source: downtowndurham.com).

fields.title: Purple S.T.E.A.M.
fields.description: The purple woven sculpture outside the Main Branch of the Durham Public Library is one of the largest permanent 3D-printed public sculptures in the United States. The sculpture’s purple color was influenced by two books frequently mentioned as favorites at the library: “The Color Purple” by Alice Walker and “Harold and the Purple Crayon” by Crockett Johnson. Both the fabrication process and the color of the sculpture represent the library’s commitment to STEAM education (source: durhamcountylibrary.org).
